gomodel:SYNGO_1833  a     owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: 6/11/2017 Pim\n\nPrior information:\n- NRPs are known binders of semaphorins. NRP-1 is necessary for Sema3A-mediated repulsive guidance events (Raper, 2000; Pasterkamp and Kolodkin, 2003; Fujisawa, 2004)\n\n(not shown): sNRP-1 blocked the promoting effect of Sema3A on branching formation\nFig.3: Exposure to Sema3A increases PSD-95 immunoreactive clusters in cultured cortical neurons, and sNRP-1 (dom.neg.) blocked the promoting effect of Sema3A on PSD-95 cluster formation (overexpression, cortical neurons)\nFig.4: Colocalization of clusters of PSD-95 and NRP-1 on spine-like protrusions on dendrites. (overexpression, cortical neurons)\nFig.5: Sema3A increases PSD-95- and synapsin I-immunoreactive clusters in cultured cortical neurons (overexpression, cortical neurons). Experimental description: Mouse cortical cultures are used for the staining.\n\nLiteral From M&M:\n\"Primary cortical culture. Cortical neurons derived from embryonic day 16.5 (E16.5) brains of ICR mice were plated on four-well dishes (Nalgen, Rochester, NY) coated with poly-L-lysine (Sigma) at a density of 4-7x10000 cells per well and grown in Neurobasal medium supplemented with B27 and L-glutamine.\"\n\n6/11/2017 Pim\n- Overexpressed Sema3A is of unknown species. Author was contacted (goshima@med.yokohama-cu.ac.jp, dd 6/11/2017) for species information. Authors answered:\n\n\"I am Yukio Sasaki, one of authors entitled \"Regulation of dendritic branching and spine maturation by semaphorin3A-Fyn signaling\". We used \"chick\" Sema3A in this paper.\nSincerely,\nYukio Sasaki\"" ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0003-2949-9725" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0003-0662-9523" ;
        dc:date           "2018-02-12" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_BP_1833" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_9031" .

pav:providedBy  a  owl:AnnotationProperty .

